1657":"1608–1657","1583–1664":"1583–1664","1583":"1583","about 1608":"about 1608","1657":"1657","1600":"1600","after 1657":"after 1657","1664":"1664","1642":"1642","about 1603":"about 1603","1584":"1584","1609":"1609","1608":"1608","about 1583":"about 1583","1606":"1606","1648":"1648","South Holland, Netherlands":"South Holland, Netherlands","Netherlands":"Netherlands","Leiderdorp, South Holland, Netherlands":"Leiderdorp, South Holland, Netherlands","Leiden, Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, Holland, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Withaer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire) and English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wither</i> or its Old Norse cognate <i>Vitharr</i>, <i>Withar</i>.","perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a willow tree, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>withi</i> ‘willow’ (Old English <i>wīthig</i>). Compare   Withey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Withey","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a willow tree, Middle English <i>withy</i> (Old English <i>wīthig</i>)."]},{"name":"Withers","meanings":["English: variant of   Wither  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Jacob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356703,"age":1,"year":"1584","julianDay":2299604,"description":"William of Orange (1533-1584), Prince of Orange (1538-1584), Count of Nassau (1559-1584), and first stadholder of the United Provinces of the Netherlands, was assassinated by Burgundian Balthasar Gerard (25) with a handgun. Philip II of Spain had called for a volunteer assassin due to William's reluctance take a public stand on religious issues. William was succeeded by his 17-year-old son, Maurice of Nassau.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356704,"age":17,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"description":"Britain waged wars against the Dutch.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356706,"age":23,"year":"1606","julianDay":2307640,"description":"Rembrandt Harmenszoon van Rijn was born in Leiden, the Netherlands.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356707,"age":26,"year":"1609","julianDay":2308736,"description":"\"English navigator Henry Hudson, under contract to the United East India Company, sails from Amsterdam and \"\"discovers\"\"Manhattan Island and the future site of New York.\"","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356711,"age":59,"year":"1642","julianDay":2320789,"description":"Curacao became a colony of the Netherlands.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356712,"age":65,"year":"1648","julianDay":2322980,"description":"End of Eighty Years' War with Spain.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Jacob W